        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request a 3~hour (on-source) synthesis observation with the 12m array at 345~GHz in the C34-3 configuration to achieve the required
angular resolution and sensitivity. Including calibration and overhead, the total time requested for the 12m array is 6.3 hours according to the ALMA Observing Tool. We also request the ACA array to probe emission at scales that will be filtered out by the 12m array, as detailed below.

- Imaging requirements -
From our ALMA Cycle 0 data, the disk has an inner radius of about 2'' and an outer radius of 6''. Our Cycle 0 observations, with an angular resolution of about 1'', suggest the presence of two rings. To better study the radial dust distribution and possibly highlight some azymutal asymmetries, observations in Cycle 2 with better sensitivity and angular resolution are needed. A demonstration of the proposed observations to reach the imaging capabilities needed for our science goals is provided in Fig. 2 of the Scientific Justification.


- Band, array configurations and use of the ACA array -
We chose Band 7 (345~GHz) for these observations because this is the most sensitive ALMA Band to dust emission at a given integration time. 
In Band 7 the entire disk can be imaged with a single pointing (primary beam size is 18 arcsec at 345~GHz). We performed simulations of the ALMA observations with mosaic mode but although sensitivity in the otermost regions of the disk could be slightly improved in this way, a more significant loss in sensitivity (compared with the single pointing case) was found in the inner disk, at a given integration time.
We requested 0.5'' angular resolution, which is better than a factor of 2 than our previous ALMA Cycle 0 observations and will allow us to investigate in better detail the structure of the disk, down to scales of about 15 AU. This will be important to get a more precise estimate for the size of the gap which reflects into a lower uncertainty on the mass of the planet carving the gap.

We note that spatial filtering of the largest scales in the disk (from about 5 to 12'' in diameter) is expected for the selected 12m array configuration. In order to recover the emission from these scales we requested the ACA array which can perfectly cover these scales in Band 7. Given the relatively large flux of the disk, more than 30 mJy in Band 7, and the relatively large beam of the 7m compact array (5 arcsec angular resolution vs 12 arcsec diameter of the disk), the 7m array will have enough sensitivity to clearly detect the disk at high SNR at short baselines. 
We also note that the Total Power antennas those antennas are not  needed for these observations as all the flux from the source will be already recovered by the 7m compact array, and also these are continuum mode observations.

- Correlator setup -
Correlator was set to continuum mode to maximize sensitivity in dust continuum. 

- Sensitivity -
We request a rms noise of 0.016 mJy/beam in continuum at Band 7. Thanks to the higher frequency than our ALMA Cycle 0 in Band 6, a factor of 2 larger collecting area, and some Cycle 0 observations conducted in not ideal conditions, the Cycle 2 observations will be a factor 10-20 deeper than in Cycle 0 at a fixed beam size, and 3-5 times more sensitive in terms of surface brightness at the requested higher angular resolution. Fig. 2 in the Scientific Justification shows that with this sensitivity we can both well characterize the dust emission from both the inner and outer ring and also detect azimuthal asimmetries at SNR of the order of 10, in the case of a massive planet embedded in the disk.  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
