    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Mapping the structure of debris disks at sub-millimeter wavelengths allows to investigate the dynamical history of planetary systems.
The young, ~ 100 Myr old, Solar analog HD 107146 hosts one of the most intriguing debris disks. Given its broad width, face-on geometry, high brightness in the sub-millimeter, this is the best candidate to investigate in detail the interaction between a planetary system and a large population of planetesimals surrounding a young Solar like star.
Our ALMA Cycle 0 observations of this system show a tantalizing hint of a double ring structure that may represent dynamical clearing by a planet.
Thanks to the superior image quality of ALMA in Cycle 2, these data will enable us to: 1) confirm the double ring structure, measure the gap size and estimate the mass of the embedded planet carving the gap; 2) investigate the presence of azimuthal asymmetries, such as particles trapped in resonance by a planet similar to or more massive than Jupiter. These ALMA data will provide a new and unique measurement of gap size and azimuthal asymmetries in a debris disk that will set the baseline for future observational and theoretical work on these structures.</prp:abstract>
